{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180912182127|859239697","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"James_Comer_(politician)","to":"James Comer (politician)"}],"pages":{"35103698":{"pageid":35103698,"ns":0,"title":"James Comer (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-11T11:47:41Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = James Comer\n|image        = James Comer official congressional photo.jpg\n|state        = [[Kentucky]]\n|district     = {{ushr|KY|1|1st}}\n|term_start   = November 8, 2016\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Ed Whitfield]]\n|successor    = \n|office2      = Agriculture Commissioner of Kentucky\n|governor2    = [[Steve Beshear]]<br>[[Matt Bevin]]\n|term_start2  = January 2, 2012\n|term_end2    = January 4, 2016\n|predecessor2 = [[Richie Farmer]]\n|successor2   = [[Ryan Quarles]] \n|state_house3 = Kentucky\n|district3    = 53rd\n|term_start3  = January 2001\n|term_end3    = January 2, 2012\n|predecessor3 = Billy Polston\n|successor3   = [[Bart Rowland]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1972|8|19}}\n|birth_place  = [[Carthage, Tennessee]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education    = [[Western Kentucky University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])\n|website      = {{url|comer.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''James R. Comer Jr.'''<ref name=\"VoteSmart\">{{cite web |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/35169/james-comer-jr#.VT02HJOjdlE |title=James Comer, Jr.'s Biography |publisher=Votesmart.org|accessdate=May 2, 2015}}</ref> {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|m|\u0259r}} (born August 19, 1972) is an American politician from the Commonwealth of [[Kentucky]] who currently represents the state's  [[Kentucky's 1st congressional district|1st congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]]. He previously served as the Agriculture Commissioner of Kentucky from 2012 to 2016 and in the [[Kentucky House of Representatives]] from 2000 to 2012.\n\nComer sought the Republican nomination for [[Governor of Kentucky]] in the [[Kentucky gubernatorial election, 2015|2015 election]]. After losing, he successfully sought the Republican nomination for {{ushr|KY|1}} to succeed fellow Republican [[Ed Whitfield]]. On November 8, 2016, Comer won both a full term to the seat for the next Congress and also a special election which allowed him to serve the remainder of Whitfield's term.\n\n==Early life and education==\nComer is a native of [[Carthage, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=C001108|title=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress}}</ref>  He received a bachelor's degree in agriculture from [[Western Kentucky University]] in 1993.<ref name=wkyu />  In college, he served as President of the Kentucky [[Future Farmers of America]]. After college, he started James Comer, Jr. Farms,<ref name=Mays>{{cite web|url=https://maysville.kctcs.edu/news/ky-commissioner-of-agriculture-james-comer-to-keynote-farm--family-night-at-mctc.aspx|title=KY Commissioner of Agriculture James Comer to Keynote Farm  Family Night at MCTC|website=maysville.kctcs.edu}}</ref> a {{convert|950|ha|order=flip}} farm with his family,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paducahsun.com/PrintPage/042716_PS_Comer-for-Congress|title=Comer combines experience in bid|website=www.paducahsun.com}}</ref> and he is also co-owner of Comer Land & Cattle Co.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kyfbnewsroom.com/comer-commemorates-may-beef-month-in-kentucky/|title=Comer commemorates May beef month in Kentucky|date=May 10, 2013|publisher=}}</ref> He also served as a director of the South Central Bank for twelve years.<ref name=wkyu>{{cite web|url=http://wkyufm.org/post/james-comer-s-quest-pass-bold-agenda-gets-bumpy#stream/0|title=James Comer's Quest To 'Pass A Bold Agenda' Gets Bumpy|first=Ryland|last=Barton|publisher=}}</ref> He served as President of the Monroe County Chamber of Commerce from 1999 to 2000.<ref name=wkyu />\n\n==Kentucky House of Representatives ==\nIn 2000 Comer was elected to the [[Kentucky House of Representatives]] at the age of 27.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/politics/elections/kentucky/2015/05/07/james-comer-confident-despite-gubernatorial-campaign-turbulence/70953062/|title=Comer confident despite campaign 'turbulence'|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Kentucky Commissioner of Agriculture==\n[[File:James Comer Kentucky National Guard.jpg|thumb|left|Comer speaking to members of the [[Kentucky National Guard]] in 2013]]\nIn 2011, Comer ran for the position of Agriculture Commissioner; the incumbent, [[Richie Farmer]], was [[Term limits in the United States|term limited]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentucky.com/news/politics-government/article44096538.html|title=Comer and Bob Farmer will face off for agriculture commissioner|publisher=}}</ref> In the election, Comer was the only Republican to win election to a statewide executive office,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clintonnews.net/pages/?p=3858|title=2011 \u2013 The Year In Review|publisher=}}</ref> and worked with a team of Democratic officials and under a Democratic Governor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyforward.com/ag-commissioner-james-comer-ending-first-year-in-office-as-it-began-full-steam-ahead/|title=Ag Commissioner James Comer ending first year in office as it began \u2013 full steam ahead - KyForward.com|website=www.kyforward.com}}</ref> Comer had the highest percentage of the vote of any candidate on the ballot. He raised $606,766 while his opponent raised $204,287.<ref>Kentucky Registry of Election Finance</ref> He took office on January 2012 and one of his first actions in office was teaming up with Democratic Auditor [[Adam Edelen]] to investigate his Republican predecessor's ethical issues while in office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nelsoncountygazette.com/?p=11404|title=Bluegrass Beacon: Edelen takes the farm for government transparency|date=May 4, 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThat year Comer became the chairman of the Kentucky Industrial Hemp Commission,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southeastfarmpress.com/miscellaneous/america-s-hemp-epicenter-kentucky-ag-commissioner-excites-enthusiasts|title=America's hemp epicenter: Kentucky ag commissioner excites enthusiasts|date=October 14, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> and shortly after taking office, Comer labeled the legalization of industrialized hemp as his top priority,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentucky.com/2013/08/30/2795546_comer-to-push-for-kentucky-to.html |title=Lexington, KY local and state news by the Lexington Herald-Leader |publisher=Kentucky.com |date= |accessdate=May 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bastian |first=Jonathan |url=http://wfpl.org/post/front-tv-kentucky-ag-commissioner-james-comer-hemp-gops-future-felon-voting-rights |title=Up Front TV: Kentucky Ag Commissioner James Comer on Hemp, GOP's Future, Felon Voting Rights - 89.3 WFPL |publisher=Wfpl.org |date=February 6, 2014 |accessdate=May 2, 2015}}</ref> and was \"instrumental in getting the hemp industry up and running,\"<ref name=WKM /> including the founding of several pilot programs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanereport.com/47991/2015/05/comer-growers-industry-leaders-announce-array-of-hemp-projects/|title=Comer, growers, industry leaders announce array of hemp projects|publisher=}}</ref> in an effort to restart the industrial hemp industry of Kentucky. His efforts also included filing suit against the DEA, which resulted in the DEA allowing hemp seeds to be delivered to farmers in Kentucky for the first new crops.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/smellthetruth/2015/05/12/kentucky-cbd-back-to-the-future-with-industrial-hemp/|title=Kentucky CBD: Back to the Future with Industrial Hemp|date=May 12, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Between 2014 and 2015 the hemp crops of Kentucky grew from 33 to 1700 acres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailychronic.net/2015/43035/kentuckys-2015-hemp-crop-to-exceed-1700-acres-up-from-33-acres-in-2014/|title=Kentucky's 2015 Hemp Crop to Exceed 1,700 Acres; Up from 33 Acres in 2014|date=May 8, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Comer also advocated for national hemp deregulation in Washington DC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wfpl.org/ag-commissioner-james-comer-heading-washington-talk-hemp/|title=Ag Commissioner James Comer Heading to Washington to Talk Hemp - 89.3 WFPL News Louisville|first=Kenny|last=Colston|date=April 23, 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nComer also founded the Kentucky Proud Farm to Campus program,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgdailynews.com/news/gubernatorial-hopeful-comer-speaks-about-farm-program/article_2d38f4b7-2105-591e-9e44-9269cdcb6d90.html|title=Gubernatorial hopeful Comer speaks about farm program|first=CHARLES A. MASON|last=cmason@bgdailynews.com|publisher=}}</ref> and created a mobile science centers program for primary and secondary school students to learn about agricultural sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanereport.com/23569/2013/08/comer-launches-new-mobile-science-units-to-teach-kentucky-kids-about-agriculture/|title=Comer launches new mobile science units to teach Kentucky kids about agriculture|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==2015 gubernatorial election==\n[[File:James Comer by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Comer in 2014]]\nOn August 2, 2014, during the annual [[Fancy Farm, Kentucky|Fancy Farm]] picnic, Comer announced he would seek the Republican nomination for [[Governor of Kentucky]] in the [[Kentucky gubernatorial election, 2015|2015 election]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/26181808/ag-commissioner-james-comer-announces-run-for-governor-in-2015 |title=Ag. Commissioner James Comer announces run for governor in 2015 |publisher=wdrb.com |date=August 2, 2014 |accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref> His running mate is State Senator [[Christian McDaniel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wkms.org/post/james-comer-introduces-running-mate-chris-mcdaniel-kentucky-gubernatorial-campaign-kick |title=James Comer Introduces Running Mate Chris McDaniel In Kentucky Gubernatorial Campaign Kick-Off |publisher=wkms.org |date=September 9, 2014 |accessdate=September 10, 2014}}</ref> Comer was 83 votes behind businessman [[Matt Bevin]] in the May 19, 2015 primary election. The [[Associated Press]], referring to the race a \"virtual tie\", did not call the race in favor of either candidate. In addition, Comer had refused to concede and stated that he would ask for a recanvass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wkyt.com/home/headlines/Voters-head-to-the-polls-for-the-Kentucky-primary-election-304221281.html |title=Officials say Bevin, Comer race too close to call |website=Wkyt.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref> The request for recanvass was filed with the [[Kentucky Secretary of State|Kentucky Secretary of State's]] office on May 20, 2015 with Secretary of State [[Alison Lundergan Grimes]] ordering the recanvass to occur at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. local time on Thursday, May 28, 2015.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150526004246/http://apps.sos.ky.gov/temp/ComerRecanvass.pdf] \n</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kentucky.gov/Pages/Activity-Stream.aspx?viewMode=ViewDetailInNewPage&eventID={507224B1-FF13-4A38-A778-09A1A630AB5B}&activityType=PressRelease |title=Secretary Grimes Receives Recanvass Request from James Comer and Chris McDaniel|website=Kentucky.gov |date= |accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref> Upon completion of the recanvass, Grimes announced that Bevin remained 83 votes ahead of Comer.<ref name=Atl>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/10/after-near-miss-in-kentucky-governors-race-james-comer-tries-a-congressional-comeback/448026/|title=After Near-Miss in Kentucky Governor's Race, James Comer Tries a Congressional Comeback|first=Lisa|last=Hagen|publisher=}}</ref>  Grimes also stated that should Comer want a full [[Election recount|recount]], it would require a court order from the [[Franklin County, Kentucky|Franklin]] [[Kentucky Circuit Court|Circuit Court]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wkyt.com/home/headlines/Kentucky-officials-begin-review-of-GOP-primary-results-305314511.html |title=Review shows Bevin holding 83-vote lead in Kentucky GOP primary |website=Wkyt.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref> On May 29, Comer announced he would not request a recount and conceded the nomination to Bevin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wkyt.com/home/headlines/Comer-concedes-Bevin-to-face-Conway-in-race-for-Governor-305453511.html |title=Comer concedes, Bevin to face Conway in race for governor |website=Wkyt.com |date= |accessdate=2016-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==United States House of Representatives==\n\n===2016 election===\nIn 2016 Comer entered the Republican primary election for the first congressional district of Kentucky against two other competitors. Prior to the primary, he was endorsed by both the National Rifle Association and the US Chamber of Commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wkms.org/post/audio-james-comer-talks-bid-1st-district-congressional-seat-ahead-may-17-primary|title=[AUDIO] James Comer Talks Bid for 1st District Congressional Seat Ahead of May 17 Primary|first=John|last=Null|publisher=}}</ref> In the end he won the primary with 60.6% of the vote.<ref name=Atl /> Comer was elected to the United States House of Representatives in Kentucky's District 1 with 72.6% of the vote,<ref name=WKM>{{cite web|url=http://wkms.org/post/congressman-james-comer-talks-president-trump-trade-deals-regulations-hemp|title=Congressman James Comer Talks President Trump, Trade Deals, Regulations, Hemp|first=Matt|last=Markgraf|publisher=}}</ref> defeating his Democratic opponent Samuel L. Gaskins. Voters voted separately both for who would fill the unexpired seat of predecessor Ed Whitfield from the date of the election forward, as well as who would fill the seat for the upcoming 2017-19 term, and Comer won both elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/james-comer-elected-fill-open-seat-kentuckys-1st-district|title=James Comer Elected to Fill Open Seat in Kentucky's 1st District|date=November 9, 2016|website=Roll Call}}</ref> \n[[File:James Comer swearing in.jpg|thumb|Comer being sworn in by Speaker [[Paul Ryan]]]]\n\n===Tenure===\nDuring the first few months of his tenure, Comer held several town hall meetings, where he discussed the Congress's early platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://surfky.com/index.php/christian/179-news/kentucky/119664-comer-town-hall-set-in-heart-of-farmland-usa|title=Comer Town Hall Set in Heart of Farmland USA|first=Rita Dukes Smith, SurfKY News|last=Director|website=surfky.com}}</ref> He also partnered with Murray State University to form the Congressman James Comer Congressional Agriculture Fellowship program,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://msublueandgold.org/2017/05/congressman-james-comer-and-murray-state-university-hutson-school-of-agriculture-partner-for-agriculture-fellowship/|title=Congressman James Comer and Murray State University Hutson School of Agriculture partner for agriculture fellowship \u2013 The Blue & Gold|website=msublueandgold.org}}</ref> and has advocated for the reform of agricultural legislation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wkms.org/post/congressman-comer-talks-farm-bill-ag-industry-healthcare-hopkinsville|title=Congressman Comer Talks Farm Bill, Ag Industry, Healthcare in Hopkinsville|first=Matt|last=Markgraf|publisher=}}</ref> He has also criticized the regulatory policies of Barack Obama,<ref>http://www.westkentuckystar.com/News/State/Kentucky/Comer-Talks-Tobacco-with-Secretary-of-Agriculture.aspx</ref> and supported the early domestic policies and actions of Donald Trump. Comer is a social conservative on \"same-sex marriage and abortion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wkms.org/post/was-not-act-war-comer-talks-syrian-strike-and-more-murray-business-leaders|title=\"That Was Not an Act of War\" Comer Talks Syrian Strike and More with Murray Business Leaders|first=Matt|last=Markgraf|publisher=}}</ref> In terms of foreign policy, Comer believes that the trade embargo on Cuba should be lifted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wkms.org/post/rep-comer-kentucky-ag-industry-would-benefit-lifting-embargo-cuba|title=Rep. Comer: Kentucky Ag Industry Would Benefit from Lifting Embargo on Cuba|first=Matt|last=Markgraf|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Comer voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=1|website=The New York Times|accessdate=28 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> After the bill's passing, Comer stated: \"I am proud to support this critical part of President Trump's pro-growth agenda that will fulfill this promise to the American people who have struggled under the weight of Washington bureaucrats for far too long.\"<ref name=\"OCM121917\">{{cite web|title=Congressman Comer votes for final version of Tax Cuts and Jobs Act {{!}} The Ohio County Monitor|url=https://ocmonitor.com/2017/12/19/congressman-comer-votes-for-final-version-of-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act/|website=Ohio County Monitor|accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n\n===Domestic issues ===\n\n==== Health care====\n\nComer supports the repeal of the [[Affordable Care Act]] (\"Obamacare\").<ref name=\"VS2016\">{{cite web|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/35169/james-comer-jr/#.WkR6b1Q-dE4|website=Vote Smart|accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic issues ===\n\nIn 2016, Comer called the Obama administration's final budget a \"disaster in the making.\" He believes that federal spending must become \"under control\" to not create \"mountains of debt.\"<ref name=\"VS2016\"/> In 2017, he voted for the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|Tax Cuts and Jobs Act]] which is anticipated to add an estimated $1.49 trillion to the national debt.<ref name=\"Bryan111017\">{{cite web|last1=Bryan|first1=Bob|title=The giant Senate tax bill barely squeaked by a critical test|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/trump-tax-plan-senate-bill-deficit-debt-2017-11|website=Business Insider|accessdate=28 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== International issues ===\n\n==== Immigration====\n\nComer opposes [[amnesty]] and [[sanctuary cities]]. He supports [[Executive Order 13767]], the building a wall along the [[Mexico-US border]].<ref name=\"VS2016\"/>\n\n===Social issues===\n\n==== Abortion ====\n\nComer is [[pro-life]].<ref name=\"VS2016\"/>\n\n==== Cannabis ====\n\nComer supports declassifying [[marijuana]] as a Schedule 1 narcotic. He supports growing [[hemp]]. He says there is \"simply not enough support for medical marijuana legalization across the board.\"<ref name=\"Harvey122317\">{{cite web|last1=Harvey|first1=Laura|title=Comer meets with residents|url=http://www.the-messenger.com/news/local/article_66c1f945-9f6e-504a-8994-6539bbd908b9.html|website=The Messenger|accessdate=28 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== LGBT rights ====\n\nComer opposes [[same-sex marriage]].<ref name=\"VS2016\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nComer is married to Tamara Jo \"TJ\" Comer and has three children, one boy and two girls. He is a Member of First Baptist Church of Tompkinsville, but has attended Forks of the Elkhorn Baptist Church since his election to the office of Agriculture Commissioner.<ref name=\"VoteSmart\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/kycomer |title=Comer Tweets about events and services at \"Forks of the Elkhorn [Southern] Baptist Church\" with relative Frequency|publisher=Twitter.com|accessdate=May 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2015, he was accused of physical and mental abuse by Marilyn Thomas, a woman he dated while attending Western Kentucky University in 1993.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gerth |first=Joseph |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/politics/elections/kentucky/2015/05/04/james-comer-domestic-violence/26901137/ |title=College girlfriend says James Comer abused her |work=[[The Courier-Journal]]|date=May 5, 2015|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref> According to ''[[Atlantic Magazine]]'', Comer has stated that he believes the accusation was a political stunt in order to hinder his gubernatorial campaign.<ref name=Atl />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|James Comer}}\n*[https://comer.house.gov/ Congressman James Comer] official US House site\n*[http://jamescomer.com Campaign site]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Kentucky/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/James_Comer_%5BR-1%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|jamescomer02}}\n* {{ CongLinks | congbio = C001108 | votesmart = 35169 | fec = H6KY01110 | congress = james-comer/C001108 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Richie Farmer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Agriculture Commissioner of Kentucky|years=2012\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ryan Quarles]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Kentucky\n| district=1\n| before=[[Ed Whitfield]]\n| start= November 8, 2016\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Warren Davidson]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n| title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|Seniority in the U.S. House of Representatives]]\n| years =366th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dwight Evans (politician)|Dwight Evans]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{KY-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\